Data Summary

The data that is chosen for doing R analysis is the 2016 American Community Survey (ACS) 5-year Public Use Microdata Samples (PUMS). These are the actual responses that are taken by the ACS community. The data is divided into population data and household data.

For all the analysis done in this document, the household data is used. The household data contains information about various household characteristics and the types of households. The variables that this analysis uses are as follows,

  • RT : Record Type
    It specifies whether the household is a housing record(H) or a Group Quarters(GQ) Unit.

  • SERIALNO : Serial Number
    It is the housing Unit/GQ person serial number.It is a unique identifier.

  • ADJHSG : Adjustment Factor for housing dollar amounts.
    The adjustment factors are,
    1045360 .2012 factor
    1030392 .2013 factor
    1013801 .2014 factor
    1012636 .2015 factor
    1000000 .2016 factor

  • NP : Number of people associated with the housing record.
    00 .Vacant unit
    01 .One person record (one person in household or any person .in group quarters)
    02..20 .Number of person records (number of persons in household)

  • ACR : lot size
    b .N/A (GQ/not a one-family house or mobile home)
    1 .House on less than one acre
    2 .House on one to less than ten acres
    3 .House on ten or more acres

  • BATH : Bathroom or shower.
    b .N/A (GQ)
    1 .Yes
    2 .No

  • BDSP : Number of bedrooms.
    bb .N/A (GQ)
    00..99 .0 to 99 bedrooms

  • ELEP : monthly Electricity cost
    bbb .N/A (GQ/vacant)
    001 .Included in rent or in condo fee
    002 .No charge or electricity not used
    003..999 .\(3\) to \(999\)

  • REFR : Refrigerator
    b .N/A (GQ)
    1 .Yes
    2 .No

  • RMSP : Number of Rooms
    bb .N/A (GQ)
    00..99 .Rooms

  • WATP : Yearly water cost
    bbbb .N/A (GQ/vacant)
    0001 .Included in rent or in condo fee
    0002 .No charge
    0003..9999 .\(3\) to \(9999\)

  • RWAT : hot and cold running water
    b .N/A (GQ)
    1 .Yes
    2 .No
    9 .Case is from Puerto Rico in 2013 or later, RWAT not applicable

Methodology

As we saw in the graph of missing values in the summary section above, there are several variables which are missing the values. Out of them, ACR variable has the most missing values. Now, that we know there are many missing values, we will filter out rows containing these missing values as follows,

h_abcd <- h_abcd %>%
  filter(!is.na(ACR) & !is.na(ELEP) & !is.na(WATP) & !is.na(REFR) & !is.na(RMSP) & !is.na(BATH) & !is.na(BDSP) & !is.na(RWAT))
head(h_abcd)

In this way, we have filtered out all the rows in the dataset that had missing values by using the filter function from dplyr.But Doing this has certain problems. We are doing analysis on only partial data. So whatever results we get from this data may be entirely different than what would we have gotten if the data were complete. So this method might skew the analysis. But since we have majority of the data with us for analysis, we use this method to handle the missing values.

As we have seen in the boxplots in the summary section, there are many outliers in the data of the number of people, number of bedrooms and the number of rooms variables. We find the extreme values in each of the attributes by using the outlier function in the outliers package as given below and then make a barplot of it,

out <- c(outlier(h_abcd$NP),outlier(h_abcd$ACR),
              outlier(h_abcd$BDSP),
              outlier(h_abcd$RMSP),outlier(h_abcd$ELEP), outlier(h_abcd$WATP))
#Making a matrix of the outliers with their corresponding 
mat.out <- matrix(data=out, nrow=1, ncol=6, byrow=TRUE)
rownames(mat.out) <- c("Extreme outlier")
colnames(mat.out) <- c("NP", "ACR", "BDSP", "RMSP", "ELEP", "WATP")
mat.out
##                 NP ACR BDSP RMSP ELEP WATP
## Extreme outlier 20   3   19   30  660 4600
#Making a bar plot of the matrix
barplot(mat.out, col="RED", main="Bar plot of Extreme outlier values according to attributes", xlab="Attributes", ylab="Extreme values")

The above bar plot gives the outlier values for the concerned variables. It shows that the outlier values for NP is 20 and so on. Now that we have some understanding of the outliers, we now replace the extreme values as outliers by the median by using the rm.outlier in the outliers package.

h_abcd$NP <- rm.outlier(h_abcd$NP, fill=TRUE, median=TRUE, opposite=FALSE)
h_abcd$ACR <- rm.outlier(h_abcd$ACR, fill=TRUE, median=TRUE, opposite=FALSE)
h_abcd$BDSP <- rm.outlier(h_abcd$NP, fill=TRUE, median=TRUE, opposite=FALSE)
h_abcd$ELEP <- rm.outlier(h_abcd$ELEP, fill=TRUE, median=TRUE, opposite=FALSE)
h_abcd$WATP <- rm.outlier(h_abcd$WATP, fill=TRUE, median=TRUE, opposite=FALSE)
h_abcd$RMSP <- rm.outlier(h_abcd$RMSP, fill=TRUE, median=TRUE, opposite=FALSE)

Hence, we have replaced the extreme values by the median. Since, median is not affected by the outliers, it is a good approach to replace outliers with median instead of mean because mean is affected by the outliers. So replacing the outliers with mean affects the mean of the entire dataset and skews the results drastically. So we replaced the outliers with median in our analysis.

We examine the boxplot of the number of bedrooms without and compare it with the previous boxplot with outliers. Referring the above boxplot,

boxplot(h_abcd$BDSP, main = "Boxplot for Number of bedrooms", xlab="Number of bedrooms")

Looking at the boxplot, it is seen that the outlier which was at the bottom of the plot earlier has been replaced with the median. Also, the one extreme point on the upper center of the plot has also been replaced likewise. Now the data has become right skewed now because the median has become almost similar to the 1st quartile.

Now that we have handled outliers and the missing values, we have to adjust the cost of electricity and water using the ADJHSG variable in the data. This is because the data is collected over the 5 years and hence we have to adjust the dollar values for the inflation. We do this adjustment by multiplying the values in the ADJHSG variable with the ELEP and WATP data respectively.

#Making a new variable ELEP_A and WATP_A which are the adjusted amounts
h_abcd <- h_abcd %>%
  mutate(ELEP_A = ADJHSG * ELEP,
         WATP_A = ADJHSG * WATP)
head(select(h_abcd, ADJHSG, ELEP, ELEP_A, WATP, WATP_A))

As seen in the above table, the variables ELEP_A and WATP_A contain the adjusted dollar values. Doing this enable us to take yearly inflation into account. Thus, this helps to get us more accurate results in terms of money. Therefore, we will be using the variables ELEP_A and WATP_A in our analysis from now on.

Now that we have handled the missing values and the outliers and adjusted the dollar amounts according to yearly inflation, we will now try to find some interesting relationships between the variables in the dataset.

We now do a t statistical test on the variables giving the cost of electricity and water to check if the costs are approximately similar. We do this by using the t.test function in R. It has the null hypothesis as The two samples do not have a significant difference in the mean and alternate hypothesis as The two samples have a significant difference in their mean. We check the significance using the 5% significance level.

t.test(h_abcd$ELEP_A, h_abcd$WATP_A)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  h_abcd$ELEP_A and h_abcd$WATP_A
## t = -1383.9, df = 5180600, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -295889043 -295052136
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 154770630 450241220

Looking at the value of the test above, the p-value is very less than 0.05 significance level. Hence, we reject the null hypothesis. Hence, we see that there is a significant difference in the costs of electricity and water. This test does not reveal anything very much interesting because we can reach the same conclusion by looking at the summary statistics in the summary section.

It is expected that the more number of people living in the house, the more average electricity cost will be incurred. But surprisingly, the table above shows that for a house with 16 people and 19 people, the average electricity cost is and respectively. This trend could be analysed further in the findings section. A similar trend analysis for water cost would be done too in the findings section.

We can also check if there is any relationship between the number of people living in the house (NP) and the number of bedrooms in the house. For this, we use the spearman correlation test in R. The null hypothesis is The data is linearly independent. and alternate hypothesis is the data is linearly dependent. The code is as follows,

cor.test(h_abcd$NP, h_abcd$BDSP, method="spearman")
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  h_abcd$NP and h_abcd$BDSP
## S = 1.1145e+14, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##      rho 
## 0.999994

According to the above test result, the p-value is very less than 0.05 significance level. Hence, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there is a relationship between the number of people living in the house and the number of bedrooms in the house. We see that the value for rho is almost 1. Hence, we can say that there is a positive correlation between the two variables. We analyse this relationship further in the findings section.

Now we do a regression model with the Number of people(NP) as the response variable and Number of bedrooms(BDSP), Electricity cost(ELEP_A) and water cost(WATP_A) as the explanatory variables. The code is as follows,

#Tranforming ELEP_A to its square root
ELEP_A1 <- sqrt(h_abcd$ELEP_A)
model1 <- lm(ELEP_A1 ~ BDSP+WATP_A+NP+ACR, h_abcd)
summary(model1)

Looking at the summary of the model, lets now interrept the various aspects of the model,

Formula Call : The function that gives the formula that was used to create the model.

Residuals : It is basically the difference between the actual value of the response variable and the values of the response variables that the model predicted. Looking at our residuals, it is seen that the residuals are distributed approximately normally.

Coefficients : The constants in a simple linear regression model represent the slope and the intercept terms such that the resultant fitted line is closer to the data points in our dataset. The estimated coefficient is the intercept and slopes. In our model, it represents the expected value of the square root of the cost of eletricity(Since we transformed ELEP_A to its square root) when all the explanatory variables are 0; that is, when there are no people living in the house, when the lot size is 0, when the water cost is 0 and when the number of bedrooms is also 0.

The second, third, fourth and fifth rows give the slope. For BDSP, the slope is 456.5374854.This means that for every 1 bedroom addition in the house, the cost of electricity goes up by 456.5374854.For, WATP_A, the slope is 8.178538110^{-7}. This means that This means that for every 1 dollar increase in the cost of water, the cost of electricity goes up by 8.178538110^{-7}. For NP, the slope is 179.1472167.This means that for every 1 additional person in the house, the cost of electricity goes up by 179.1472167. For, ACR, the slope is 1194.3743455. This means that This means that for every 1 acre increase in the size of the lot, the cost of electricity goes up by 1194.3743455. In all the above cases, to get the actual increase in the electricity cost, we have to square it because we have applied square root transformation to it.

The standard error gives the average amounts by which the coefficient estimates vary from the actual average value of our response variable(The electricity cost). In our model, it looks like the values of standard errors are pretty large and hence, we could say that the predicted values may not be reliable for this regression.

The t-value measures the amount by which our standard deviations of the coefficient estimates are away from 0. Since, in all the cases, the t-value is away from 0, we can say that there is a relationship between the cost of electricity and number of people, lot size, water cost and number of bedrooms.

The p-value gives the probability of observing any value that is greater than or equal to t. The p-values for BDSP, WATP_A, NP and ACR are 3.983888810^{-12}, 0, 0.0064725, 0 respectively. Since, all the p-values are less than 0.05 significance level, we can conclude that there is a significant relationship between all of our explanatory variables and our response variable.

Residual Standard error gives the quality of the regression fit and gives the amount by which the predicted value of the response variable will deviate from the true regression line. In our model, the residual standard error is 3710. So we can say that the actual electricity cost may deviate from the true regression line by 3710 dollars on average.

The R-squared statistic provides a measure of how well the model fits the data. We use the multiple R sqaure value because we created a simple linear regression model. For our model, the multiple R-squared value is 0.0809226. This means that roughly 8.092262 of the variance found in electricity cost can be explained by the predictor variables; BDSP, ACR, WATP_A, NP.

F-statistic is also a good indicator to find the relationship between response and the predictor variables. For our model, the f-value is 104376.9. Since, our value is very large than 1, we can reject the null hypothesis which says that there is no relationhip between the concerned variables and we can thus conclude that there is a relationship between the response and explanatory variables.

P-value of the f-statistic : Since, our p-value is 2.2e-16 which is very less than 0.05, we can say that our model is a bettern regression fit than an intercept only model.

The diagnostic plots of the regression model are as follows:

plot(model1)

Interpretation of the diagnostic plots:

Residual Vs. Fitted Plot : This plot shows the error residuals versus the fitted values.The spread indicates the patterns in the variance and the red line gives an idea about the residual movement. In our plot as seen above, there is no distince pattern to the residuals and they are spread around the horizontal line. So we can say that the variables that we built the model for don’t have any non-linear relationships. It should be noted that the response variable; ELEP_A has been square-root transformed.

Normal QQ Plot : This plot tells us if the residuals are normally distributed. Looking at our plot, it looks like the residuals follow the dotted line pretty closely. Hence, we can say that our p-values could be believable. It should be noted that the response variable; ELEP_A has been square-root transformed.

Scale-Location Plot : It indicates the spread of the data points across the range of predicted values. The red line indicates that the residuals have uniform variance across the range. With this plot, we check the data for Homoscedasticity. (i.e variance should be reasonably equal across the predictor range). In our plot, the red line is reasonably horizontal except for the end where it goes a little up. Hence, at the right of the plot, we see that the residuals are spread wider. Hence, the property of does not hold for Homoscedasticity our model.

Residuals Vs. Leverage : This plot is used to find any influential observations that can influence the results of the regression model. For this, it uses the Cook’s distance. The dotted red lines are the cook’s distance and we consider a case as an influential case if it lies beyond the dotted red lines in the upper and the bottom right corner. In our plot, there are no points lying beyond the dotted red lines. Hence, we can say that there are no influential observations in the data.

Discussion

Summarising the analysis, we tried to find out any interesting trends in the people saying yes or no to the question regarding bathrooms, running hot/cold water and refrigerator. But we didn’t find anything substantial. Then we found out that a majority of the houses are located on a land less than one acre. We also found that a majority of the houses have 2 people living in the house. From our analysis, we found out that almost 30% of all the recorded houses have 2 people living in the house and the house built on a land less than one acre. We compared the costs for electricity and water for this proportion of people. We found that they spend more on electricity. We found the reason as disproportionate number of rooms in the house as compared to the number of people actually living in the house. Even if there is only 1 person living in the house, the house has 6 rooms. There is a linear increasing trend in the number of bedrooms and the number of people living in the house. We analysed the influence of one outlier in this analysis and found that it does not affect our analysis drastically. According to our regression model, we can say that there is a relationship between our response variable; Electricity cost and the predictor variables; Water cost, lot size, Number of people and number of bedrooms. There are no influential cases in our regression model.

There are several potential limitations to this analysis. First of all, we eradicated only the most extreme outlier in the data. There may be still many outliers in the data that were not the most extreme but nevertheless outliers which this analysis doesn’t account for. Secondly, this analysis doesn’t account much for factor variables in the data like REFR, RWAT and BATH because of the fact that all the household data recorded had bathrooms, hot/cold running water and regrigerators. So, we couldn’t find any impact on the other variables if the house didn’t have those 3 characteristics. The analysis didn’t control for any missing values in the sense that we eradicated all the rows having any missing values in them. So, we may have lost some information there which could have altered the results of the analysis. The regression models that the analysis came up with are fairly believable in the sense that they show that there is a linear association between the discussed variables.

I have about 40% confidence in the analysis that I have done above and I would surely revise it if I have to present it to the policy makers. I do believe in the conclusions that I have reached but there could be certain aspects in the data that I could have failed to account for. For this reason, I would definitely revise it if I get a chance to present this analysis to the policy makers.
